snippet.textDisplay:
Using crispr for data transfer is such a weird tangent of the concept, Riley. I don't even know how you got there.
For background, crispr has been the next big thing in gene editing for the better part of a decade because it has the potential to be highly specific in what code it recognizes in order to cut and insert genes into the correct place. This is advantageous compared to earlier methods like retro virus, because a retro virus will insert DNA, but with low specificity which means it can potential insert into cancer suppression genes, increasing your chance of cancer. There are multiple delivery methods and they either can only carry a very small strand, have low specificity, or low efficacy. There was a study involving several immunodeficient newborns who were given gene therapy with retrovirus delivery method. All were monitored growing up, and all developed leukemia but were successfully treated.
